node.accessibility_caption: Photo by MIT on July 30, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
KnittedKeyboard II, developed by Responsive Environments (@res.env) PhD student Irmandy Wicaksono (@irmandyw) and demonstrated by Viral Communications PhD student Mike Hao Jiang (@mikehaojiang), is a multi-modal, soft, and stretchable electronic textile musical interface customized and fabricated with digital knitting and functional fibers.

Inspired by the theremin and the unique tactile properties of knitted textiles, the keyboard is responsive to touch, pressure, stretch, and proximity, allowing performers to play discrete notes, as well as trigger continuous effects and modulations with virtuosity. The prototype helps broaden the scope of fabric-based interactive surfaces, from novel musical controllers, wearables, to smart objects. 

Learn more: https://www.media.mit.edu/projects/knittedkeyboard-ii/overview/ or link in profile

Reposted from @mitmedialab

node.accessibility_caption: Pavarin Bhandtivej is standing in Killian court. He is wearing a white collared shirt with narrow pink stripes. He is looking off camera and he is smiling.

node.text:
Through MIT’s new master’s program in data, economics, and development policy, Pavarin Bhandtivej seeks to bring data to bear on policymaking in Thailand. 

Q: What would 5-year-old you say to you today?
A: Wow, I’ll grow up to be a big guy and study at MIT! When I was 5, I was very thin and never thought I would become this big! I also never imagined I would have a chance to study at MIT.

Q: What is your favorite virtual online activity?
A: Watching comedy on YouTube. It allows me to relax and laugh after hours of hard work.

Q: Name something you did not know about MIT until you got here.
A: MIT and MIT alumni gave birth to so many inventions and discoveries, from wind tunnels and the first air-conditioned building to GPS and World Wide Web! I always knew that MIT is a world-renowned institute of higher education and academic research, but prior to joining MIT, I never knew that it is a birthplace of so many inventions that we use every day. 

See link in profile to learn more about Pavarin Bhandtivej.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by MIT on July 21, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and skyscraper.

node.text:
A student-run effort is collecting messages from around the world, using nanotechnology to etch them on a disk, and sending the disk to the International Space Station. The HUMANS project aims to send a message that space is for everyone. “We want to invite the world to submit a message to our project website — either text or audio, or both! — sharing what space means to them and to humanity in their native languages,” says project co-founder Maya Nasr, a graduate student in the Department of Aeronautics and Astronautics. “Our goal is to use art and nanotechnology to create a symbol of unity that promotes global representation in space and brings awareness to the need for expanded access to the space sector worldwide.” Read more about the project, see link in profile.

Image courtesy of Nasr and Zhang
HUMANS project co-founders Lydia Zhang (left) and Maya Nasr

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by MIT on July 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and eyeglasses.

node.text:
On an historic day for space, we remember the many women who've contributed to space history, including Apollo 11, which landed on the moon 52 years ago today. One individual who helped make it happen was Elaine Denniston, a key punch operator in the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory, which developed Apollo’s guidance and control software before spinning off to become the independent Draper Lab. As a key puncher, Denniston input and sometimes edited the data she received from programmers on the project. “I would be reading [the code] and I’d go back and say, hmm, I think this should have had a period or it should have had a right paren or something,” she said in a 2019 interview. After MIT, Denniston pursued a career in law, retiring in 2012. Listen to the interview, see link in profile. 

Photo and interview via @mitblackhistory and @wehackthemoon

node.text:
SMART researchers develop a method for rapid, accurate virus detection: Four times faster than conventional PCR methods, new RADICA approach is highly specific, sensitive, and resistant to inhibitors. “The last year has shown us the importance of detecting viruses quickly and accurately, and RADICA can help fill existing gaps in this area,” says National University of Singapore Professor Hanry Yu, co-corresponding author and co-lead principal investigator at SMART CAMP. “Cell therapy products have a very short shelf life, and patients are usually in need of treatment urgently. Current sterility tests need around 14 days, which is too slow for clinical needs, but RADICA shortens the process into hours.” Read about the research, see link in profile.

#viruses #research #disease #PublicHealth #VirusDetection #BiologicalEngineering #medicine #pandemic

node.accessibility_caption: Shen Li gets safe assistance with dressing using his team’s human-aware motion planning algorithm.

node.text:
Getting dressed with help from robots: A human-aware motion planning algorithm addresses the safety gap in collaboration between robots and humans. “Developing algorithms to prevent physical harm without unnecessarily impacting the task efficiency is a critical challenge,” says MIT PhD student Shen Li, a lead author on a new paper about the research. “By allowing robots to make non-harmful impact with humans, our method can find efficient robot trajectories to dress the human with a safety guarantee.” Read about the research and watch a video, see link in profile.

#robots #robotics #algorithm #research #LimitedMobility @mit_csail
